{"qid": "q073", "question": "Why can PostgreSQL confirm a commit without flushing every changed data page to disk?", "expected_answer": "Because of write-ahead logging: only the sequentially-written WAL file must be flushed to guarantee durability; data pages can be written later, since they can be redone from WAL after a crash.", "qtype": "vocab-mismatch", "gold": [{"doc_id": "postgres/wal-intro", "locator": "only the WAL file needs to be flushed to disk", "grade": "primary"}]}
